{{Pashtuns}} '''Pashtunization''' ({{lang-ps|پښتون‌ جوړونه}}), also called '''Pathanization''',<ref>{{cite book|last=Nayak|first=Pandav|title=Pakistan, society and politics|year=1984|publisher=South Asian Publishers|location=University of Michigan|pages=189}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ahmed|first=Akbar S.|title=Pakistan Society: Islam, Ethnicity, and Leadership in South Asia|year=1997|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0195778373|pages=108}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Institute of Objective Studies (New Delhi, India)|title=Journal of Objective Studies, Volume 1|year=1989|publisher=Institute of Objective Studies|pages=39}}</ref> is a process of [[culture|cultural]] or [[linguistics|linguistic]] change in which someone or something non-Pashtun becomes accultured to [[Pashtun people|Pashtun]] influence. The Pashtun people are the largest [[ethnic group in Afghanistan]] and the second largest [[ethnic group in Pakistan|in Pakistan]].
==Dynasties and settlements== {{See also|List of Pashtun empires and dynasties}} [[File:Nomads in Badghis Province.jpg|left|thumb|Tents of Afghan [[nomad]]s in [[Badghis Province]] of [[Afghanistan]]. Known in [[Pashto language|Pashto]] as ''[[Kuchi people|Kuchans]],'' they are mostly [[Ghilzai]]s who migrate seasonally. Farming villages came into existence in Afghanistan about 7,000 years ago.<ref Name=Dupree3>{{Cite book|title=An Historical Guide to Afghanistan |last1=Dupree |first1=Nancy Hatch |authorlink=Nancy Dupree|volume=First Edition|year=1970|publisher=Afghan Air Authority, Afghan Tourist Organization |location=Kabul|isbn=|pages=492|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T__DHAAACAAJ&dq=inauthor:%22Nancy+Hatch+Dupree%22&source=gbs_navlinks_s|accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref>]]
People become Pashtunized when they settle in [[Pashtunistan|Pashtun-dominated areas]] and adopt [[Pashtun culture]],<ref name=Banting/> either by adapting the [[Pashto language]] or absorbing [[Pashtunwali]] customs. Pashtunization is a specific form of [[cultural assimilation]] and has been taking place in Pashtun-populated regions of [[Afghanistan]] and [[Pakistan]] for several centuries.
{{quote|"In the eighth and ninth centuries ancestors of many of today's [[Turkic languages|Turkic]]-speaking [[Afghan (name)|Afghans]] settled in the [[Hindu Kush]] area (partly to obtain better grazing land) and began to assimilate much of the [[Pashtun culture|culture]] and [[Pashto language|language]] of the [[Pashtun tribes]] already present there."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lcweb2.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/r?frd/cstdy:@field(DOCID+af0002) |title=Islamic Conquest |work=Craig Baxter |publisher=[[Library of Congress Country Studies]] on [[Afghanistan]] |year=1997}}</ref>|Craig Baxter|[[Library of Congress Country Studies]]}}
The [[Khalji dynasty|Khalji]] were originally [[Turkic tribes]] who had long domiciled in Afghanistan and gradually adopted the [[Pashtun culture]]. Some of them left the area during the [[Mongol invasion of Central Asia]] towards the [[Indian subcontinent]], where they built empires such as the Khalji dynasty of [[Delhi Sultanate|Delhi]]. They are considered by historians as ethnic Afghans (Pashtuns).<ref>{{cite book|title=History of medieval India: from 1000 A.D. to 1707 A.D. |last1=Chaurasia|first1=Radhey Shyam |authorlink=|volume=|year=2002|publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Distributors |location=|isbn=81-269-0123-3|page=28|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8XnaL7zPXPUC&source=gbs_navlinks_s |accessdate=2010-08-23|quote=The Khiljis were a Turkish tribe but having been long domiciled in Afghanistan, and adopted Afghan habits and customs. They were treated as [[Afghanistan|Afghan]]s in [[Delhi Sultanate|Delhi Court]]}}</ref><ref name="Parmar">{{cite book|title=South Asia: a historical narrative |last1=Yunus |first1=Mohammad |authorlink=|author2=Aradhana Parmar|volume=|year=2003|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |location=|isbn=0-19-579711-6|page=97|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=opbtAAAAMAAJ&source=gbs_navlinks_s |accessdate=2010-08-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=World and Its Peoples: The Middle East, Western Asia, and Northern Africa |last1=Cavendish |first1=Marshall |authorlink=|volume=|year=2006|publisher=Marshall Cavendish |location=|isbn=0-7614-7571-0|page=320|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j894miuOqc4C&source=gbs_navlinks_s |accessdate=2010-08-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9045252/Khalji-Dynasty |title=Khalji Dynasty |work=[[Encyclopædia Britannica]] |publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica Online |accessdate=2010-08-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Pearson General Studies Manual 2009, 1/e |last1=Thorpe|first1=Showick Thorpe Edgar |authorlink=|volume=|year=2009|publisher=Pearson Education India |location=|isbn=81-317-2133-7|page=63|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oAo1X2eagywC&source=gbs_navlinks_s |accessdate=2010-08-23}}</ref>
Pashtunization may also refer to the [[Pashtun diaspora|settling of Pashtun tribes]] onto lands where non-Pashtun tribes live<ref name="Meri">{{cite book |last=Meri |first=Josef W. |author-link=Josef W. Meri |title=Medieval Islamic Civilization: An Encyclopedia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H-k9oc9xsuAC |year=2006 |publisher=Taylor & Francis |isbn=0-415-96691-4|pages=713|chapter= Sedentarism}}</ref> or more broadly the erosion of the customs, traditions and language of non-Pashtun peoples due to the political power and regional influence of the Pashtuns.<ref>Lansford, Tom (2003) ''A Bitter Harvest: US foreign policy and Afghanistan'' Ashgate, Aldershot, Hants, England, {{ISBN|0-7546-3615-1}}, page 16: "The modern history of Afghanistan has witnessed a "Pashtunization" of the state as the customs, traditions and language of the Pashtuns have combined with the groups political power to erode the distinctive underpinnings of Afghanistan's other groups.<sup>FN20</sup>". FN20 cites: US, Department of the Army, ''Afghanistan: A Country Study'', 5th ed. reprint (Washington, DC.: GPO, 1985) page 108.</ref> This occurred in the [[Peshawar]] sub-region in the early 16th century, during the period of the Suri dynasty of Delhi.<ref name="Arlinghaus">"the Pashtun conquest of the Peshawar subregion in the early sixteenth century meant the Pashtunization of the area", Arlinghaus, Joseph Theodore (1988) ''The Transformation of Afgham Tribal Society: Tribal Expansion, Mughal Imperialism and the Roshaniyya Insurrection, 1450-1600'' Thesis/dissertation, Duke University, p.17, [http://www.worldcat.org/wcpa/oclc/18996657 OCLC 18996657]</ref> It intensified in the mid-18th century under Pashtun emperor [[Ahmad Shah Durrani]], when he conquered non-Pashtun territories and established the [[Durrani Empire]].<ref name="Meri"/> During the reign of [[Abdur Rahman Khan]] in the late 19th century, some Pashtuns settled in the north of the country, while [[Turco-Persian|Tajiks]] from the north were brought to the south. This was done for political reason, mainly to prevent [[Russian Empire|Russian]] invasion. In the meantime, thousands of [[Hazara people|Hazaras]] left [[Hazarajat]] to settle in [[Quetta]] (now in [[Pakistan]]) and [[Mashad]] in what is now [[Iran]].<ref>O. Roy, ''Ethnic Identity and Political Expression in Northern Afghanistan'', in ''Muslims in Central Asia: Expressions of Identity and Change'', 1992, {{ISBN|0-8223-1190-9}}.</ref>
==Modern influences== Some Pashtunization attempts were later made in the early part of the 20th century by the [[Mohammed Nadir Shah|Musahiban]]<ref>{{cite book|title=The fragmentation of Afghanistan: state formation and collapse in the international system |last1=Rubin |first1=Barnett R.|authorlink=Barnett Rubin|volume=|year=2002|publisher=Yale University Press |location=|isbn=0-300-09519-8|page=66|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=laG03iJF7t8C&source=gbs_navlinks_s |accessdate=2010-08-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Post-Soviet Central Asia |last1=Atabaki |first1=Touraj |authorlink=|author2=John O'Kane |volume=|year=1998|publisher=Tauris Academic Studies in association with the International Institute of Asian Studies |location=|isbn=1-86064-327-2|page=208|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KwZpAAAAMAAJ&source=gbs_navlinks_s |accessdate=2010-08-27}}</ref> or more recently by the [[Taliban]] (read [[Talibanization]]).<ref>United States, Congress, House, Committee on International Relations (2003) '' United States Policy in Afghanistan: Current Issues in Reconstruction '' (Hearing Before the Committee on International Relations, House of Representatives, One Hundred Eighth Congress, First Session, June 19 and October 16, 2003), G.P.O., Washington, DC, p. 104, {{ISBN|0-16-071157-6}}</ref> Some non-Pashtun ethnic groups who live in close proximity with Pashtuns have adopted [[Pashtunwali]].<ref name=Banting>{{cite book|title=Afghanistan the People |last1=Banting |first1=Erinn |authorlink=|volume=|year=2003|publisher=Crabtree Publishing Company |location=|isbn=0-7787-9336-2|page=14|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fl8cd15sc7wC&source=gbs_navlinks_s |accessdate=2010-08-27}}</ref>
